{"/service/ndnp/mb/batch_mb_allspice_ver01/data/sn83020847/00517171025/1923110801/0632.xml":{"full_text":"2\nNational Editorial Discussion International\nPoincare\u2019s \u201cIsolation\u201d\n'A conquerable change, the impor\ntance of which it is as yet difficult\nto appraise, is made by the reported\ndecision of Belgium and Italy not tc\nsupport Premier Poincare in the re\n<trictions which he seeks to impose\nUpon the inquiry into Germany\u2019s\n\u2022Mity to pay. The formula sug\ngested at Brussels is \u201cto examine\n\u201cGermany\u2019s capacity to matte repa\n\u2022rations,\u201d and it is understood that\nthis satisfies both Italy and Great\nBritain; there is no reason why it\nshould not also satisfy the United\nStates, which is acquiring a direct\ninterest in Gete*ny\u2019s economic and\nfinancial condition, not only through\nthe claims for war damages which\n\u25a0were advanced another stage yes\nterday by the mixed claims commis\nsion, but through the prospect, em\nphasized yesterday at Washington,\nthat it will soon be necessary to ar\nrange for the sale of foodstuffs to\nGermany to avert famine. At Wash\nington the news of the decision of\nItaly and Belgium to support what\nis in effect the American view was\nreceived with gratification, though\ncaution was shown in discussing the\nprobable effects of this new align\nment.\nIn Paris this new shift has been\n\u25a0watched with some uneasiness, and\nthere is even absurd talk of an ef\nfort to \u201cisolate\u201d France, to which\nthe visit of Lloyd George is sup\nposed in some mysterious way to\nliave contributed. To this effort is\nnow ascribed the stubborn refusal of\nPremier Poincare to make conces\nsions; scenting a plot for his isola\ntion, we are given to understand, he\nrefused all the more stiffly to sanc\ntion discussions in which he would\nobviously be in a minority. The ex\nplanation would be more convincing\nif he had ever shown the least dispo\nsition to unbend when Belgium and\nItaly were supporting him, and Eng\nland, if any of the allies, was \u201ciso\nlated.\u201d\nIsolation, however, is too weighty\na wmrd in diplomacy to be used to\ndescribe the position of a govern\nment which happens to find itself, on\n\u2022ome issue of common concern, in a\nminority of one. Isolation in its nor\nmal diplomatic sense means strip\nping a rival of allies and friends as\nin the case of Germany after the\nwar. France is very far from being\nstripped of allies and friends by the\nfact that its allies and friends differ\nwith Premier Poincare on one point\nof procedure. A slight concession\non his part, instead of an icy stiffen\ning against opposition to his views,\nwould make friendly collaboration as\npossible as ever.\nThere has been talk of action by\nthe allies without the participation\nof France, and such talk will in\nevitably be increased by the new at\ntitude of Belgium and Italy. Such\naction is not desired by the\nUnited States which has through\nout stressed the necessity for united\naction. If the new shift is regarded\nhonefully in Washington it is not\nbecause the isolation of Premier\nPoincare is desired, but because it is\nhoped that under the new conditions\nhe may see his way to make some\nslight concession which will make\npossible an inquiry of a genuine and\nhelpful sort. There can be no isola\ntion of France except by its own\nwill.\nu Great Britain Accepts\nH To the British government it'\nmight hardly have seemed worth\nwhile to proceed with the plan for a\ncommission of experts under the se\nvere restrictions imposed by Pre\nmier Poincare but for the prospect\nthat even so limited an inquiry would\ninvolve contact with the United\nStates. To a great extent Great\n(Britain and the United States look\nat the present problems of Europe\nin the same way. They desire set\ntled peace, the return of prosperity\nand reduction of the excessive mili\ntary establishments which stand in\nthe way of prosperity and peace. If\nthere existed any common council\nin which they could co-operate, their\nrepresentatives, so far as these ma\njor issues are concerned, would usu\nally be found on the same side. This\nis the British view, and it is support\ned to some extent by the reluctance\nof the French to arrange any con\nferences on terms which would per\nmit the United States to co-operate.\nIn a small way the plan for a com\nmission of experts does leave room\nfor American participation, and to\nthe British government this is evi\ndently the decisive point- Even if\nthe investigation itself should ac\ncomplish little it might open the\nway, in some indirect fashion, to\nfurther contacts that would offer\nlarger possibilities.\nSomewhat similar considerations\nmay perhaps influence our own gov\nernment toward going on with the\nproject in spite of the reservations\nimposed by Premier Poincare. In a\nsettlement of the reparations ques\ntion that would permit the recon\nstruction of Europe the United\nStates is of course deeply interested,\nand not wholly for selfish interests,\nthough the continued prosperity of\nour own country is closely bound up\nWith conditions abroad. The United\nStates is not so obviously interested\nin what Germany can pay to the al\nlies next year or the year after that\nor in how the bill is to be collected,\n\u00abNb\u00a3 ianytigatinn on the lines\nlaid down by France were to lead to\nnothing else it might seem hardly'\nworth while for the United States\nto take part in it even m an informal\nway.\nIt is quite possible, however, that\nthe adoption, even on a small scale,\nof the principle of calling in disin\nj terested experts as advisers might\nJ constitute an important precedent.\nThe various allied governments have\nhad plenty of experts at their dis\nposal ever since the reparations\nquestion came up; on technical ques\ntions these experts have even met\nin conference, though their delibera-\nI tions have been handicapped by in\nstructions from their several govern\nments. But the attempt to deal\nwith even a limited part of the rep\narations question by referring it to\nan advisory body of experts left\nfree to examine it in a detached and\nscientific spirit would be an innova\ntion that might prove important\neven if the immediate results were\nsmall.\nSuch a commission, if really ex-1\npert and entirely free, could hardly I\nfail to call attention to the intricate\nI character of the reparations prob-\nj lem which cannot thus be sliced into|\nsmall pieces for examination without\nI taking account of the whole as well\nas of the parts. What Germany\ncan pay in the next few years, the\nquestion which Premier Poincare is\nwilling to have taken up, depends\nlargely on its ability to borrow mon\ney for economic rehabilitation, and\ni this in turn depends, precisely as\nI when the committee of bankers look\ned at the matter last year in Paris,\nupon Germany\u2019s credit, which can\nnot possibly be separated from its\ntotal obligations under the treaty of\nVersailles. Thus however narrowly\nthe commission may be limited, its\ninvestigations must logically point to\nthe need of going beyond those lim\nits for light upon essential points.\nA small beginning, therefore, would\ngive no cause for discouragement if\ntime were assured for fuller develop\nment of the principle involved. If\nthis were the year 1920 or even 1921\nsuch a beginning might seem rather\nhopeful. The question now is wheth\ner disaster can be staved off long\nenough to permit such a gradual\ngrowth of a more realistic way of\nhandling reparations. While the\nstatesmen of Europe have been deal\ning with unrealities Germany has\nbeen steadily disintegrating, and\nhowever fast the experts work they;\nmay be unable to keep pace with j\ncatastrophic events. The crisis is\nquite grave enough to justify the\nconference of the powers for deal\ning with it which was the preferred\nmethod suggested by Great Britain.\nEven if unrestricted, a commission\nof experts which would have been\ninvaluable even a year ago, mightl\ncome too late, and fear of this is of\ncourse intensified by the restrictions\nput upon its work. But since it is\napparently the sole means available\nof doing anything at all, the more\npromptly and energetically it is\npressed the better. The race with\nruin is getting hot.\nCross Purposes\nWashington, Paris and London\nare finding it difficult to understand\neach other. Our government, it was\nstated Friday, has had no official\npresentation of the attitude of\nFrance since the reply last week to\nthe.first British note, and even this\nreply was given orally. The infor\nmation on the strength of which it\nwas unofficially given out at Wash\nington, first that Premier Poincare\u2019s\nconditions would not interfere with\nAmerican participation in the com\nmission of experts, and later, that\nthese restrictions threatened to\nmake the whole project abortive, is\ndrawn from the reports of the\nFrench premier\u2019s speeches and from\nthe interpretation put upon these\nspeeches by the French foreign of\nfice.\nIn London,which does not disguise\nits anxiety to have the United States\nrepresented in such an inquiry, a\nmore hopeful conclusion is drawn\nfrom the same documents, but it isl\ndifficult to avoid the suspicion that\nthe reasoning by which the conclu-:\nsion is reached has been influenced\nby desire. Whereas Washington\nwas frankly disappointed at the ten-\u25a0\nor of Poincare\u2019s speech at Nevers,\nThursday, British commentators pro- I\nfess to find in it a more conciliatory\ntone than in his speech of last Sun\nday; his not repeating certain things\nis hopefully taken as showing a de\nsire to soften the restrictions al\nready set forth,\nThat Paris does not put this in\nterpretation on the Nevers speech,\nbut leans rather to Washington's\nview is indicated by the attempt to\nminimize it on the ground that it\nwas meant for \u201chome consumption.\u201d\nThis explanation, however, only\nmakes the confusion worse, since at\nNevers Poincare was for the first\ntime addressing not a red-hot Na\ntionalist audience, but one strongly\ntinctured with socialism, and if he\nwas speaking for \u201chome consump\n\u2018tion\u201d we should seek evidence of it\nin those passages which got most\napplause, such as the declaration,\n\u201cWe covet no territory; we respect\nj \u2018the liberty of peoples; we desire to\n\u2018retain with our allies the most am\n\u2018icable relations.\u201d\nNeither is ths hopeful London\nlilk BEKINiiMELD WEEKLY KEFUBUCAN: IHUKBDAY, NOVEMBER 8, IHZ3\nview borne out by the Paris sum\nmary of the French reply delivered\nThursday to the British government,\nin which France accepts with cor\ndiality the proposed collaboration of\nthe United States, but desires it to\nbe clearly understood that the sug\ngested inquiry should bear solely on\nthe present capacity of Germany and\nthat it respect all the rights held\nby the reparations commission under\nj the treaty of Versailles. Simulta-\nI neously the French foreign office is\nsues another statement declaring\nI that examination of Germany\u2019s fu\nture ability to pay would be equiv\ni alent to examination into a reduc\ntion of France\u2019s claim, for which\nPremier Poincare is the less pre-;\npared because he is convinced that\nthe sole reason for proposing the ex-\npert commission is to reduce Ger-\nmany\u2019s debt to the allies. The pro- j\nposal, it is added, was made in such j\na way that he could scarcely decline\nit, bat he could and did surround his\nacceptance with guaranties against\nany such result.\nEven these assurances do not sat-;\nisfy implacables like \u201cPertinax\u201d of\nthe Echo de Paris, who is fearful j\nthat if a commission of experts be-1\ngins to investigate the ability of;\nGermany to pay it will find even that\nquestion linked with the capacity to j\nraise money on credit and thus with j\nthe question of total liabilities. In:\nthis country, in some quarters, it i\nhas been urged that our government\naccept Premier Poincare\u2019s restric-1\ntions in the hope that even a re\nstricted inquiry might have some\nsuch result. The United States\ngovernment, however, now indicates\nin an informal way that it does not\ncare to enter a conference held un\nder false pretenses; its aim is not\nto try to outwit the French premier\nbut to secure the co-operation of\nFrance. If this is not forthcoming\nit Will be for our government to de\ncide whether to drop the whole mat\nter or make further efforts to bring\nabout an agreement. The simplest\ncourse would be to withdraw, but\nstirring of new hopes which even a\ntentative step toward a settlement\nproduced shows the importance of\nutilizing every possible diplomatic\nresource before abandoning so meri\ntorious a project. It may be that\nwith but a little more persuasion\nand compromise a formula can still\nbe found which Premier Poincare\nwould accept and -which our own\ngovernment would consider work\nable.\nLloyd George\u2019s Farewell\nGood judgment was shown by\nLloyd George in approaching New\nYork from the west instead of from\nthe east, and his speech at the Met\nropolitan Opera house Friday night\nwas more impressive than it would\nhave been earlier. Hilaire Belloc not\nlong ago advised British statesmen\nvisiting America to come on an un\nfashionable steamer and to take a\nlook at Main street and Zenith City\nbefore settling down in New York, j\nPossibly our distinguished visitor I\nhad this advice in mind when after I\nlanding he hurried off to Canada,\nand then made a tour of the West\nbefore he circumspectly approached\nWashington and New York.\nIn these travels he had covered\nsome thousands of miles and had\naddressed 79 audiences instead of\nthe eight originally planned for, and\nhe must have come to New York\nknowing a good deal more of Ameri\nca than when he arrived. Geography\nhas never been his strong point, but\nhe is remarkably quick in learning\nfrom talk and personal contact, and I\nhis visit to the new world must have\nbeen highly instructive. If he should\nagain take office, which is very far\nfrom lying outside the range of pos\nsibilities, the first-hand information\nacquired during his stay in America\nwould be an element of no little im\nportance.\nAfter the failure of the United\nStates to ratify the treaty of Ver\nsailles Lloyd George was one of the\nfirst of European statesmen to real\nize how disastrous might be an es-:\nfort to execute the treaty without\ni the aid of America, and he lost no\nopportunity to work for the partici\ni pation of this country. While he\nwas prime minister British policy\nwas shaped largely toward promot\ning closer relations with the United\nStates, and this part ?of his program\nhas been adopted by his successor.\nDesire for friendly relations with\nthe United States played no small\npart in hastening the Irish settle\nment, a long forward step, even if\nirreconcilable Irish republicans who\ntried to annoy Lloyd George in New\nYork failed to give him due credit\nfor it.\nIn this as in other matters. Great\nBritain has made so great an effort\nto propitiate American opinion that\nit is not si rprisfng that Britons\nshould feel that in so grave a crisis\nAmerica might reciprocate a little\nby using its great influence in sup\nport of reconstruction. Of late the\ndisposition of Americans to recog\nnize the moral duty of the United\nStates to do what it safely can has\nmaterially increased and the appeals\nof Lloyd George have not fallen on\ndeaf ears. It can be said also that\nhis speeches have been both tactful\nand persuasive, and that American\ncomment upon them has been almost\nwholly favorable.\nSuch critical remarks as have\nbeen made have in great part re\nlated to Lloyd George\u2019s own share\nof responsibility for the mes- which\nAmerica is now asked to help clear\nup. Of this he cannot be acquitted,\nbut discussion of past errors does\nj not help greatly in dealing .with\npresent problems, and it is fair to\nj say that as soon as the magnitude\nof the error was discovered Lloyd\nGeorge set to work manfully to cor\nrect it In his speech, he was con\ntent to defend the treaty of Ver\nsailles as \"the best treaty that could\n\u201cbe negotiated under the conditions\n\u2018of the time,\u201d but at the time he was\ni probably very far from realizing\nhow bad a treaty it would prove in\npractice.\nThere is much truth in his remark\ni that \"every treaty depends not\n\u2018merely upon its intrinsic merits but\n\u2018upon the methods and the manner\n\u2018of its execution.\u201d This is peculiarly I\ntrue, however, of the treaty of Ver\nsailles because it is so huge and ill\ndigested a document full of inhar\nmonious and even incompatible\nthings.\nTo make a statue, it has been\nsaid, a sculptor has only to take a\nblock of marble and remove what\nis superfluous. The treaty of Ver\nsailles should perhaps be likened to\nrubber rather than Parian marble,\nbut it contains stuff enough for a\ndozen masterpieces, all quite differ\nent from the Laocoon group which\nis actually emerging as Poincare\nplies the chisel. The mistakes of\nLloyd George were grave, but he\nhas at least tried to make amends,\nand his visit to America has been\nin the interest of reconstruction.\nOn the Way\nSenator Hiram Johnson\u2019s solemn\nspeech of warning at Oakland, Cal.,\nconfirms recent reports that he was\nunder pressure from his political\nfriends to take advantage of the first\nopportunity to announce his presi\ndential candidacy. He saw nothing\nbut the most dreadful political en\ntanglements -in European affairs in\ncase Secretary Hughes\u2019s plan of par\nticipation in an advisory conference\nof economic experts on German rep\narations were carried into effect. He\neven misconstrued remarks by Lloyd\nGeorge concerning Germany\u2019s pos\nsible recalcitrancy after the advis\nory committee\u2019s report as showing\nthat the United States would be\nobliged to become a debt collector\nfor France and the allies. Lloyd\nGeorge was the particular imp of\ndarkness who had come here with\nthe deliberate purpose to intrigue\nfor America\u2019s entanglement. Is it\nnot high time for Hiram Johnson to\nstep forward and save the country\nfrom the perilous adventures con\ntemplated by Secretary Hughes and\nthe President?\nThat is the question which Sena\ntor Johnson must soon answer. In\nview of the present indifference of\nthe Coolidge administration to a\nconference restricted as severely as\nPoincare would limit it, the senator\nmay already have waited too long.\nThe foundation for this attack was\nflimsy enough, as things were; for\nhow could a sane man sincerely ar\ngue that the participation by. an\nAmerican economic expert, without\nofficial standing formally recognized\nby his own government, in an advis\nory conference on German repara\ntions would violate American prin\nciples and precedents or, endanger\nthe peace and security of this na\ntion Yet if even this participation\nin a European conference should\nnow fail to materialize, Hiram John\nson\u2019s political plight would be sad\nindeed. To substantiate his belief\nthat the administration was slipping\ndown the slope to perdition, he could\nthen point to nothing but the nomi\nnation of Mr Kellogg of Minnesota\nto be embassador to Great Britain.\nIf this new advisory reparations\nconference actually comes off, John\nson will see his way clear. There\nwill be a tremendous tub thumping\nas he takes the field as a presiden\ntial candidate in order to rescue\nAmerica from an \u201cunwise leader\n\u2018ship.\u201d If there is another presidency\nin the slogan \u201cKeep out of Europe,\u201d\nJohnson will be there to seize it. If\nthere is not another presidency in\nit, at least, he will enjoy the sport\ning thrills of trying for it He is\nfirst and last our Hiram, and vain\nare the hopes that he will now be\ncome celebrated for his unobtrusive\nways. The current prediction that\nhis candidacy will be announced be\nfore Congress convenes may be pre\nmature, but all the signs weather\nwise are that he is on the way.\nSamuel Walker McCall\nGov McCall at his best inspired\nthe pride of the people of Massa\nchusetts because of his natural gifts,\nhis scholarship, his independence of\nthought and judgment and the subtle\nsuggestion which hts personality\nconveyed of the statesman cast in\nthe mold that tradition had stamped\nas peculiarly the Bay state\u2019s own.\nIf Nature had intended him to be a\nsecond Webster, it just missed the\nmark, for while he looked the part\nhe lacked chiefly that solidity and\nmassiveness which distinguished the\nolder school. Nor did he have the\nindefatigable industry and passion\nfor toil which often compensates\neven a second-rate man for lack of\ngenius or exceptional talent for pub-\nlie life.\nStill, Mr McCall was a high place\nin the esteem of the country as well\nof his own state. When he retired\nfrom Congress in 1913 he had a na\ntional reputation. The fact that he\nwas never a narrow partisan, that\nhis views on public questions were\nwell studied, that he was courageous,\nthat he was an orator of distinction\nand a scholar in history and politics\nwon for him the appreciation of ed\nucated people everywhere. Colleges\nand universities honored him with\ntheir degrees. He was welcomed as\na contributor to reviews and mag\nazines on subjects of public interest.\nHe was a very acceptable writer of\nbiography. Had he not turned to\npolitics he might have made a high\nreputation as a publicist. What he\nlacked was the punch and the power\nbehind the punch to batter his way\nthrough political obstructions to the\nposition in the Senate for which he\nwas undoubtedly fitted.\nAs governor of Massachusetts Mr\nMcCall will seem notable for two\nthings\u2014he was our governor dur\ning America\u2019s participation in the\nWorld war; and he promoted suc\ncessfully the calling of the state\nconstitutional convention of 1918\nwhich has left its impress unmis\ntakably upon our state government\nand institutions. His administration\nthus rose in importance above the\naverage, but it has sometimes\nseemed more an anticlimax to the 20\nyears in Congress than one likes to\nadmit. Doubtless this impression has\nbeen due to the earlier feeling that\npromotion to the Senate was Mr Mc-\nCall\u2019s right by virtue of his experi\nence and his talents. But that were\na superficial estimate of his career.\nHe was a most useful citizen, with\nexceptionally fine ideals of public\nservice and, in the sum, he deserves\nhigh rank among the public men of\nMassachusetts in the past 50 years.\nConnecticut Leadership\nHomer S. Cummings, former\nchairman of the Democratic nation\nal committee and now the state at\ntorney of Fairfield county in Con\nnecticut, has been credited in some\ncircles with an ambition to win the\nDemocratic presidential nomination.\nIf he nurses presidential aspirations,\nhis strong prohibition speech at the\nlaw enforcement meeting in New\nHaven Wednesday evening, is indic\native of a Democratic politician\u2019s re\naction to the present situation in the\nwettest part of the United States.\nMr Cummings has no desire to com\npete with Gov Smith of New York\nor Senator Edwards of New Jersey\nfor the leadership of the antiprohi\nbition wing of the Democratic party.\nYet Mr Cummings may more char\nitably and generously be credited\nwith a nobler motive than the polit\nical one. As the prosecuting officer\nof Fairfield county he is in very close\ncontact with the law enforcement\nsituation where the state of Connect\nicut comes nearest to the great city\nof New York. If anyone might be\nexpected to succumb to the inunda\ntion of the outlaw whisky traffic it\nis Mr Cummings. Yet he says noth\ning at all about repealing the 18th\namendment or modifying the Vol\nstead act. In his New Haven speech\nhe accepted constitutional prohibi\ntion as a permanent fact and de\nmanded nothing but enforcement of\nthe Volstead law. Nor should the\nenforcement of prohibition, he de\nclared, be left to the federal gov\nernment by the states. The purpose\nof those who advocate the withdraw\nal of state support \u201cis manifestly to\n\u2018embarrass the operations of the fed\n\u2018eral government and to render the\n\u2018constitution inoperative in certain\n\u2018parts of the country.\u201d\nThe state of Connecticut is mak\ning an exceptional record among the\nnortheastern states for enforcement\nof the prohibitory law, and this is\nthe more creditable because the Con\nnecticut Legislature has never ap\nproved the 18th amendment to the\nfederal constitution. State attorneys\nlike Mr Cummings of Fairfield coun\nty and Mr Alcorn of Hartford coun\nty are militantlyvin action and thus\nare doing very much to give tone\nand direction to public sentiment by\nshowing what can be done through\nthe complete utilisation_of enforce\nment processes. On another page in\nthis paper an article on Mr Alcorn\u2019s\nactivities outlines his conception of\nthe possibilities. It is heartening\nfrom our observation point in Mas\nsachusetts to look across the state\nboundary and see these officials,\nwho rank with Chief Justice Wheel\ner as inspfrers of a more effective\nwarfare on an illicit traffic that now\noutrages civic decency and seeks to\npollute the springs of the social\norder.\nBlame for Naval Disaster\nThe naval court of inquiry which\ninvestigated the stranding of the\nnine destroyers near Honda, Cal., on\nSeptember 8, reaches the conclusion\nthat the disaster in the first instance\nwas \u201cdirectly attributable to bad or\n'ders of judgment and faulty naviga\n\u2018tion on the part of three officers\"\non the leading vessel, the flagship\nDelphy. As a technical judgment of\nseamanship, involving no question of\nmoral culpability, this decision is\nlikely to go unchallenged. A naval\ncourt-martial will fix penalties in ac\ncordance with established rules.\nBut the court of inquiry also holds\nthe individual commanders of eight\ndestroyers responsible in lesser de\ngree, through having followed the\nleading vessel without exercising in-\nI dependent judgment, and recom\nmends that they suffer the stern\npenalty of the sea which requires a\ncaptain to lose his command if he\nloses his ship. While the public has\nno ground for doubting the compe\ntence of this finding there are as\npects of it involving justice to indi\nvidual men which properly invite\nquestioning. The report of the court\nsays:\u2014\nDivision commanders and individual\nship captains are always charged with\nthe safety of the unit under their\ncommand, no matter who leads, unless\nit is in the presence of the enemy.\nNothing can replace the use of\nsound, common sense on the part of\nthe subordinate, and, if he is not fur\nnished with sufficient Information by\nhis leader to absolutely safeguard his\nown unit or to effectively carry out his\nplan, he must ask for it himself.\nThis is incontrovertible as a state\nment of abstract principle. But noth\ning in the pres^ummary of the re\nport shows by whose orders and\nthrough whose decision the individ\nual judgments of the ship captains\nwere subordinated to the will of the\nsquadron commander or the com\nmander of the flagship. The prac\ntice of following the leader could not\nhave been adopted voluntarily by\nthe captains for that particular\ncruise without precedent. Is there\nnot reason to suppose that American\ndestroyer squadrons were habitually\nbeing navigated on this unsafe prin\nciple? If so, faulty teaching or\nfaulty administration would seem to\nenter into the case.\nThe Railroads Say No\nThe Interstate Commerce commis\nsion is already engaged in investi\ngating the railroad freight rates on\ncoal and on the 14th is to begin a\ngeneral investigation of rates on\ngrain products throughout the coun\ntry. While the eastern roads could\nhave put into effect a reduction of\nthe rates on export wheat, as re\nquested by President Coolidge, they\nhave chosen not to do so for various\nreasons, one of which is that the\nsubject is so soon to be investigated\nby the commission. The President\u2019s\nother suggestion, that the rates on\nexport and domestic coal be equal\nized, is not embraced in the reply\nof the executives, possibly for the\nsame reason but more prrbably be\ncause the situation complained of is\nnot different from inequalities in\nrates on coal transported wholly\nwithin the United States. That\nthere is need of some examination\ninto the economic structure of coal\nrates is to be inferred from Mr\nHultman\u2019s statement before the In\nterstate Commerce commission in\nBoston yesterday.\nThe railroads have sound business\nreasons for refusing the reduction\nasked for although it was not at va\nriance with the economics of railroad\nrate making. Apparently for the\npresent they see no necessity for\nmaking concessions of a political na\nture. If rate reductions are to come\nthe best precedent dictates that they\nbe made by the commission after in\nvestigation.\nThe Airplane Industry\nThe assistant secretary of war,\nDwight Davis, chose Detroit as the\ncity in which to make a statement\nregarding aviation intended to reach\nthe eyes of the entire American peo\nple. He declared that the air serv\nice should be authorized to begin a\n10-year building program in an ef\nfort to catch up with other nations.\nMore serious than our deficiency in\nthis branch of the service was the\nstate of the airplane industry in this\ncountry. This industry, he said,\nwas \u201cstarving to death,\u201d while \u201cfor\n\u2018eign nations were building up a\n\u2018flourishing airplane industry, capa\n\u2018ble of immediate conversion to war\n\u2018needs.\u201d What he recommended was\na building program \u201cfor purely\n\u2018training and defensive purposes.\u201d\nMr Davis would probably not have\ndescribed the nation\u2019s airplane in\ndustry-, in whose behalf he was in\ncidentally making an appeal, as\n\u201cstarving to death\u201d unless he were\nexpressing the views of those re\nsponsible as financiers or managers\nfor the conduct of that industry. A\ncasual survey would lead to the\nsame conclusions. There is virtually\nno commercial demand for airplanes\nand, in spite of numerous enthusias\ntic prophecies, there !s no immediate\nprospective demand. The problem\nbefore the people is to discourage\ncompetitive building of airplanes as\na form of armament in rivalry with\nother nations and to devote our en\nergies to the developing and per\nfecting of the airplane and to pro\nmoting skill in its use.\nThe government buys airplanes\nfor its fighting services and makes\nuse of airplanes in the mail service\nand some other departments. The\ndemand for an airplane mail service\nis chiefly agitated by those who de\nsire the further rendering of gov\nernment assistance to aviation, not\nby persons eager to obtain more\nrapid transportation of mails. Bet\nter results might be obtained if this\namount of money were expended on\nthe building and use of airplanes for\nexperimental and training purposes.\nIn this country the government is\nthe only important customer of the\nairplane industry. That industry\nmust receive enough orders to main\ntain itself or the government must\ntake over airplane manufacture and\nexperimentation.\nWhen Mr Davis implies that the\nairplane industry is going swim\nmingly in other lands, his words can\nbe set against a good many state\nments of contrary purport. English\narmy men, for example, are also in\nclined to be pessimistic. There, as\nin this country, the arrangements be\ntween the government and the man\nufacturers are said to be inadequate\nto support the industry on a healthy\nbasis despite the larger commercial\nuse of the airplane in Europe. The\ncase with dirigibles is declared to\nbe worse. An English major com\nplained only a few weeks ago that\nthe United States was three years\nahead of Great Britain, regardless\nof our advantage in the supply of\nhelium.\nThis same writer declared that\n\u201cthe United States was going ahead\n\u2018with great vigor in all departments\n\u2018of aeronautics.\u201d Our assistant sec\nretary of war says that the industry\nis \u201cstarving to death.\u201d It is not de\nsirable that the rivalry of other na\ntions should be employed in any\ncountry as an argument for stimu\nlating the manufacture of airplanes,\nbut the obligation to science as well\nas military requirements demands\njudicious attention.\nA New Era for Soft-Coal\nMining?\nThat the cost of soft coal mining\nin this country can be reduced by\n30 per cent is the interesting asser\ntion contained in a supplementary\nreport issued by the United States\ncoal commission. The report was\nprepared by Col Sanford E. Thomp\nson of Boston, who has investigated\nmine management in the bituminous\ncoal regions at the commission\u2019s be\nhest\nThe gist of the recipe is the re\nplacing of unskilled labor by ma\nchinery, particularly for undercut\nting and loading, the chief items of\nlabor cost. Illustrating the saving\nthat would thus be possible, the\nreport cites the case of one machine\nloader that excavated nearly 400\ntons a day, which is to be contrasted\nwith the ordinary 12-ton product of\nthe hand miner. Reducing of waste,\nconcentration of operations and les\nsening of danger, it is pointed out,\nwould naturally follow from the im\nproved methods. While the num\nber of workers required would be\nmuch less, the degree of skill needed\nby those remaining would be great\ner, and the demand in other indus\ntries for labor of the kind that\nwould be displaced exceeds the sup\nply. Since adoption of the machine\nmethod of production would neces\nsarily be gradual, on account of the\nvariety of conditions in the various\nmines, the transition should, it is\nbelieved, be accomplished with\nlittle friction.\nPrevious suggestions for reducing\ncosts of coal mining have stressed\nthe necessity for better organiza\ntion. If mining can be done effect\nively and economically by a much\ngreater use of machinery the mana\ngerial problems would obviously be\nautomatically simplified. The super\nfluous mine would at the same time\ntend toward disappearance. What\nthe attitude of labor would be is\nproblematical. It is familiar history\nthat displacement of large numbers\nof workers by labor saving ma\nchinery has often been vigorously\nopposed, with little apparent regard\nto future benefits to be expected. A\nsomewhat new situation, however,\nhas doubtless been created by the\nnew immigration policy. The report\nat least holds out hope that an end\nis coming to the chaotic conditions\nwhich have prevailed with varying\ndegrees of cost and annoyance since\ncoal began to be mined.\nOklahoma Indians and the Klan\nA phase of the Oklahoma ques\ntion which has been given little pub\nlic consideration is the treatment of\nthe Indians, who have not been al\ntogether blessed since Indian Terri\ntory became a state, and especially\nsince it became the home of oil boom\ners and speculators. In a letter to\nthe Andover Townsman, Warren K.\nMoorehead, the well known archeol\nogist, who is also a member of the\nUnited States board of Indian com\nmissioners, gives some first-hand in\nformation which ought to be useful\nto the army of good citizens of the\nstate who are jealous of its fair\nname, and to Congress as well.\nMr Moorehead declares that \u201cIn\n\u2018dian citizenship amounts to nothing\n\u2018and seldom will a white jury give an\nIndian justice.\u201d About 2000 Indians,\nhe says, are interested in oil wells,\na few thousand are fairly well to do;\n\u201cthe rest are paupers or verging on\n\u2018pauperism.\u2019\u2019 White people who\nwould not think of defrauding each\nother have felt free to cheat the In\ndians out of their property. But\nWhites as well as Indians who have\ngained unexpected riches from oil\nhave been swindled to an extent\nconstituting \u201ca scandal and a dis\n\u2018grace.\u201d Mr Moorehead cites im\npressive authority in support of\ncharges of gross official favoritism\nto the advantage of big and little\nplunderers.\nThe bearing of these observations\nupon the present political situation\nin the state is suggested by this\npassage: \u201cThere is no record of the\n\u2018Ku Klux taking a hand in the pro\njection of Indian minors, orphans\n\u2018or adults in Oklahoma. They are\n\u2018chiefly concerned in beating up un\nfortunate women and men, and ter\n\u2018rorizing Negroes.\" And this one,\nconcerning Gov Walton: \u201cProbably\n\u2018many things done by him should\n\u2018have been left undone. He may\n\u2018have pardoned criminals from the\n\u2018penitentiary. At the same time, he\n'has showed courage and backbone\n\u2018in attempting to curb the activities\n\u2018of the Ku Klux Klan and those\n\u2018who have swindled and despoiled\n\u2018the poor Indians.\u201d\nAccording to a correspondent of\nthe New York Times, who has been\nstudying conditions in the Klan-rid\nden states of Texas, Arkansas and\nOklahoma, the Klan has apparently\nreached the hight of its power in\nOklahoma and it is even expected\nthat after the case of Gov Walton I\nhas been disposed of a drastic anti-\nKlan law will be enacted. Its pre/\ntense of championship of the opjF\npressed and effective work for lavl..\nand order is too hollow, it woul<^ e\nseem, for it to last much longerij\nBut even if such claims could b\u00ab\nbacked by a record of accomplish^\nment it would of course still be with\nout valid excuse for existence. The\nsooner it subsides the easier will be\nthe task of the state\u2019s eloquent\nchampions.\nIs There an American People?\nDisturbed by the current tendency\nto centralization, a considerable\nnumber of persons are again vigor-\nously demanding a return to the\nprinciple of state\u2019s rights. In mak\ning this demand, they exalt the fed-.'\neral constitution as a document^\nnot only sanctioning their view oW\nthe problem of federal and statq* I\nauthority but condemning the legisfo\u2019\nlative tendencies of which they disc',\napprove. Their reasoning seems to\u00a3\nconfuse two things\u2014the machinery* I\nof lawmaking and the purposes foC\nwhich at a particular time that ma- i\u2019\nchinery is being employed.\nThe chief justice of the supremqfj\ncourt of Illinois, Floyd Eugene\nThompson, speaking at the banquet Fj\nof the Associated Industries of Mas- S'\nsachusetts, asserted:\u2014\nThere is. no such political unit inj\nthis country as the \"people o\u00a3 that\nUnited States.\u2019\u2019 Ths \"people of the\u00a3\nseveral states\" established the federal\ngovernment and they now conduct it.\nThis is an extreme statement of the t\ntheory of state sovereignty. It is'\nnot a theory that finds complete\nsupport in the language of the fed\neral constitution or in the form of\nour government, which, while recog\nnizing the states even in the appor\ntionment of representatives, secures\nto the people direct representation in\nthe lower branch of Congress. The\nfirst words of the federal constitu\ntion are these: \u201cWe the people of\n\u2018the United States.\u201d While the\nfounders left large powers with the\nstate governments, there is no doubt\nthat it was their intention to form\na national government capable of\nexercising its power immediately\nupon the citizens, not through the\nmedium of the states. In a letter\nto Jefferson, Madison wrote:\nIt was generally agreed (at the con\nstitutional convention) that the ob\njects of the Union could not be se\ncured by any system founded upon\nthe principle of a confederation of\nsovereign states. Hence was\nembraced the alternative of a govern\nment which, instead of operating on\nthe states, should operate without\ntheir intervention on the individuals\ncomposing them.\nThe people of the United States are\na political unit for administrative\npurposes so far as federal laws era\nconcerned. They are virtually a\nunit in the Election of a President,\nand even in the election of senators\nthe state is little more than a regis\ntering mechanism. According to\ngood authorities, the real sovereign\nty of the people in the United States\nis guaranteed by their unlimited\npower of amending the federal con\nstitution. It is not guaranteed by\nany rights they possess under the\nstate constitutions.\nJudge Thompson's indictment of\npaternalism would have been more\neffective if less involved with con\nstitutional theory. He bitterly as\nsailed the federal maternity act, not\non the ground that aid was unneed\ned, but that the act created federal\njobs and provided \u201ca suffering and.\n\u2018poverty-stricken mother\" merely\nwith \u201can abundance of advice.\" This\nis perhaps a valid criticism; for\nsurely advice will not go far to pro\nvide \u201cfood and shelter and proper\n\u2018medical care,\u201d for the want of which*\nin Judge Thompson\u2019s own words,\n\u201cmany a mother suffers daily and\n\u2018many a babe\u2019s life is sacrificed. 1\nEvery agency and device of govern\nment should be tested and judged\non its merits, just as every agency\nand device of industry and commerce\nis, in theory at any rate, testgiand\njudged.\nHotels in Summer and Winter\nNew England hotel men, at their\nrecent gathering in Worcester, ex\npressed no dissatisfaction over the\npast summer\u2019s business, but were\nadvised to make more aggressive\nplans for the future. A. C. Judd\nof the Elton at Waterbury said that\nsummer hotel business in New Eng\nland was changing every year as\npeople\u2019s habits changed. Country\nclubs are growing in popularity in'\na way that may interfere with hotel\npatronage and girls\u2019 camps are re\ngarded as competitors/>f the hotels.\nMany people sought their summer\nrecreation in automobiles and did J\nnot close their homes. I\nThe hotels are indeed affected by 1\nthe changing habits of the people.\nBut they have not been powerless j\nthemselves to effect changes in 1\npeople\u2019s habits. The old-fashioned 1\nsummer hotel, with its sports and its\nrather elaborate social life, created'\na demand for the kind of entertain\nment offered. A few hotels have\nretained their old ways, but\u2019 in\ngeneral nowadays the summer hotel;\ncaters either to the touring motorist I","height":"25757","width":"19908"}}
